00:12.960 --> 00:14.700
Hi, I'm Edwina Lowe,

00:14.700 --> 00:17.610
product specialist within the
Data Assets and Alpha Group.

00:17.610 --> 00:19.290
And, hi, I'm Eloise Goulder,

00:19.290 --> 00:21.090
head of the Data Assets and Alpha Group,

00:21.090 --> 00:24.960
which sits within the Prime
Financial Services organization

00:24.960 --> 00:27.210
within the trading business
here at J.P. Morgan.

00:27.210 --> 00:30.030
So Eloise, could we go back a few steps

00:30.030 --> 00:34.110
and talk about the creation
and reason for our team,

00:34.110 --> 00:35.880
the Data Assets and Alpha Group?

00:35.880 --> 00:36.780
Absolutely.

00:36.780 --> 00:41.010
So we created the group six
years ago, it was in 2019.

00:41.010 --> 00:42.900
And really, we created it to try

00:42.900 --> 00:46.230
and pull together two
significant functions

00:46.230 --> 00:48.300
within the trading organization.

00:48.300 --> 00:51.300
So one of them was the
market intelligence function.

00:51.300 --> 00:52.140
This is a function

00:52.140 --> 00:55.440
that has been around
for more than a decade.

00:55.440 --> 00:57.990
It predates my life at J.P. Morgan.

00:57.990 --> 00:59.850
And really, the market
intelligence function

00:59.850 --> 01:03.270
is providing on-the-pulse market dynamics

01:03.270 --> 01:05.820
and interpretation of what is going on

01:05.820 --> 01:10.820
based on political developments,
based on macro catalysts,

01:10.950 --> 01:13.830
based on results season,

01:13.830 --> 01:17.400
and what the thematic drivers
of results season might be.

01:17.400 --> 01:20.523
That is what our market
intelligence function does.

01:21.630 --> 01:22.952
But in addition to that,

01:22.952 --> 01:25.530
and we really wanted to
beef up that function

01:25.530 --> 01:28.080
and make it a true
coordinated global function

01:28.080 --> 01:29.400
when we set up the group,

01:29.400 --> 01:32.910
we also wanted to add
in the data-driven lens.

01:32.910 --> 01:34.110
That's so important,

01:34.110 --> 01:38.100
partly because our
clients' demand for data

01:38.100 --> 01:40.920
and data-driven insights
has only been increasing

01:40.920 --> 01:42.420
over that period.

01:42.420 --> 01:44.250
But it's also because it's so important

01:44.250 --> 01:46.920
that our markets insights are as unbiased

01:46.920 --> 01:48.210
as we can make them,

01:48.210 --> 01:52.410
are very tactical, are
very catalyst-driven.

01:52.410 --> 01:54.540
That's so important for our
market intelligence function.

01:54.540 --> 01:56.130
And it really goes both ways.

01:56.130 --> 01:57.870
Our market intelligence function

01:57.870 --> 02:00.660
is more powerful with
that data-driven lens.

02:00.660 --> 02:03.840
And the other parts of our
team, our Data Intelligence team

02:03.840 --> 02:05.520
and our Positioning Intelligence team,

02:05.520 --> 02:08.310
which together make up our overall group,

02:08.310 --> 02:12.090
are so much more powerful if
they have a market's nous,

02:12.090 --> 02:13.980
if they are topical,

02:13.980 --> 02:16.080
if we can bring to life those datasets

02:16.080 --> 02:18.630
with relevant market insights.

02:18.630 --> 02:19.890
Absolutely.

02:19.890 --> 02:22.260
And where do you see the intersection

02:22.260 --> 02:25.110
of those three distinct pillars
of the team coming together?

02:25.110 --> 02:27.090
Well, I do like to think the sum

02:27.090 --> 02:30.990
is so much more significant
than each one of those parts.

02:30.990 --> 02:32.610
And there are so many areas

02:32.610 --> 02:35.340
that intersect those three pillars.

02:35.340 --> 02:38.370
I mean, Edwina, your role really
spans all of those pillars.

02:38.370 --> 02:42.000
You are involved in so
many cross-group projects.

02:42.000 --> 02:44.370
Perhaps I can turn that
question back to you?

02:44.370 --> 02:47.580
Yeah, I mean, I think from my perspective,

02:47.580 --> 02:50.940
the opportunity to speak
to clients cross-teams,

02:50.940 --> 02:52.770
so pulling together
different parts of our team

02:52.770 --> 02:55.350
for our client conversations,
can be really powerful,

02:55.350 --> 02:57.630
and certainly appreciated by our clients.

02:57.630 --> 02:58.980
But in terms of our products,

02:58.980 --> 03:01.350
I think I would single out the podcast

03:01.350 --> 03:03.660
as a great example of
that team collaboration

03:03.660 --> 03:05.910
and bringing the threads
of our team together.

03:05.910 --> 03:08.280
I mean, we launched our
series three years ago,

03:08.280 --> 03:11.040
and I think it's a fantastic example

03:11.040 --> 03:14.160
of showcasing everything we do as a team,

03:14.160 --> 03:18.450
but also the opportunity to
bring together other colleagues

03:18.450 --> 03:20.490
from the wider markets business.

03:20.490 --> 03:22.770
So, for example, one of
our recurring themes,

03:22.770 --> 03:23.700
as you well know,

03:23.700 --> 03:27.270
is the retail investor and the
rise of the retail investor.

03:27.270 --> 03:28.890
So the opportunity to look at that

03:28.890 --> 03:30.510
through a number of different lenses

03:30.510 --> 03:34.560
and bring in colleagues that
can also speak to that theme.

03:34.560 --> 03:36.150
And it's interesting.

03:36.150 --> 03:37.950
I think at the outset of the podcast,

03:37.950 --> 03:42.450
we just saw it as another
means of communication,

03:42.450 --> 03:44.580
another means of content dissemination.

03:44.580 --> 03:45.750
We have the written content

03:45.750 --> 03:48.540
from our Market and our
Positioning Intelligence teams,

03:48.540 --> 03:50.730
we have the data content, the API content,

03:50.730 --> 03:52.800
which, of course, is an
enormous growth area,

03:52.800 --> 03:55.050
which I'm sure we'll talk about today.

03:55.050 --> 03:55.980
And the podcast,

03:55.980 --> 03:59.490
another audio means of
disseminating content,

03:59.490 --> 04:00.323
which, of course,

04:00.323 --> 04:03.570
has been growing across the
world and across our industry.

04:03.570 --> 04:04.440
But what I've learned,

04:04.440 --> 04:06.150
and I'm sure you feel the same, Edwina,

04:06.150 --> 04:11.150
is actually, it's a way of
creating new ideas, new insights,

04:12.930 --> 04:14.640
which you couldn't create

04:14.640 --> 04:16.710
if you didn't put those
subject matter-experts

04:16.710 --> 04:19.383
in a room together to
have that discussion,

04:20.220 --> 04:23.970
in that, so many topics
don't have a firm conclusion,

04:23.970 --> 04:26.970
it's not as simple as question,

04:26.970 --> 04:29.040
three bullets, and a conclusion.

04:29.040 --> 04:30.900
So many questions are so nuanced.

04:30.900 --> 04:35.670
You know, tackling will US
exceptionalism continue,

04:35.670 --> 04:38.730
will it last, or will other
economies start to outperform,

04:38.730 --> 04:41.700
and will other market
assets start to outperform?

04:41.700 --> 04:44.010
We are covering the rise
of the retail investor

04:44.010 --> 04:47.400
in so many markets, in US
markets, in Asian markets,

04:47.400 --> 04:49.590
and what the implications of that are.

04:49.590 --> 04:51.660
We are covering behavioral biases

04:51.660 --> 04:54.000
and the extent to which we can both try

04:54.000 --> 04:56.340
to mitigate them in investing decisions,

04:56.340 --> 04:59.170
but also how we can capitalize on them

05:00.450 --> 05:03.570
to attempt to create
alpha-generating opportunities.

05:03.570 --> 05:05.643
These are such complex topics,

05:07.694 --> 05:09.810
and most of them don't
have a clear-cut answer.

05:09.810 --> 05:11.460
It would be naive for us to assume

05:11.460 --> 05:13.590
that there is a clear-cut answer.

05:13.590 --> 05:15.900
So I do think the power of the podcast,

05:15.900 --> 05:19.620
the power of the audio
conversation, is so significant,

05:19.620 --> 05:21.810
because you can really,
you can learn so much,

05:21.810 --> 05:24.240
but also you can share
and articulate the nuance

05:24.240 --> 05:25.230
of the argument.

05:25.230 --> 05:27.510
And really, the beauty is in that nuance.

05:27.510 --> 05:29.400
Could we focus on our team name,

05:29.400 --> 05:30.990
the Data Assets and Alpha Group?

05:30.990 --> 05:33.210
I've been in the team a
little over three years,

05:33.210 --> 05:35.550
but I'm aware that the team predates me.

05:35.550 --> 05:37.530
Could you talk a little
bit about that, Eloise?

05:37.530 --> 05:38.700
Yeah, absolutely.

05:38.700 --> 05:39.533
Well, in a way,

05:39.533 --> 05:42.600
I think we do exactly
what we say on the tin.

05:42.600 --> 05:45.270
We are the Data Assets and Alpha Group.

05:45.270 --> 05:46.560
What do I mean by that?

05:46.560 --> 05:50.610
Well, we are creating
and curating datasets

05:50.610 --> 05:53.820
from across our markets
trading organization.

05:53.820 --> 05:57.090
They may be positioning-related datasets,

05:57.090 --> 05:58.350
hedge fund positioning,

05:58.350 --> 06:01.410
they might be social
sentiment-related datasets.

06:01.410 --> 06:03.090
What are our interpretations

06:03.090 --> 06:06.360
of sentiment based on
scanning the multitudes

06:06.360 --> 06:07.893
of posts on social media?

06:09.240 --> 06:10.920
So we are creating all of those datasets,

06:10.920 --> 06:12.543
but why are we creating them?

06:13.519 --> 06:15.660
Why are we in the pursuit of the creation

06:15.660 --> 06:16.980
of those datasets?

06:16.980 --> 06:18.540
It's because we're using them

06:18.540 --> 06:21.180
for predictive purposes within markets.

06:21.180 --> 06:23.280
We are using them to help have a lens

06:23.280 --> 06:25.080
on which markets and which assets

06:25.080 --> 06:27.960
and which stocks will
outperform or underperform.

06:27.960 --> 06:30.120
And therein lies the alpha term.

06:30.120 --> 06:32.580
It's all about alpha generation
at the end of the day.

06:32.580 --> 06:35.487
So we are the Data Assets
and the Alpha team,

06:35.487 --> 06:37.890
and we wouldn't want to
care about the data assets

06:37.890 --> 06:39.510
without that alpha focus.

06:39.510 --> 06:42.150
Alpha is the core of
everything that we do.

06:42.150 --> 06:45.000
So Eloise, a question
that comes up a lot is,

06:45.000 --> 06:47.940
what distinguishes us in the
Data Assets and Alpha Group

06:47.940 --> 06:50.700
from the research organization?

06:50.700 --> 06:52.350
Could you talk a little bit about that?

06:52.350 --> 06:55.950
Yes, absolutely. And we do
get that question quite a lot.

06:55.950 --> 06:58.440
So we are distinct from research.

06:58.440 --> 07:01.050
We have a very strong
relationship with research.

07:01.050 --> 07:02.130
That is critical.

07:02.130 --> 07:05.400
It's so important we understand
what research are doing

07:05.400 --> 07:08.460
and saying, whether
that's from the macro lens

07:08.460 --> 07:11.400
or the micro bottom-up stock-picking lens,

07:11.400 --> 07:13.260
or indeed the quant lens.

07:13.260 --> 07:14.730
But we are distinct.

07:14.730 --> 07:18.150
We sit within the trading
organization here at J.P. Morgan.

07:18.150 --> 07:19.320
And why are we different?

07:19.320 --> 07:20.153
Well, first of all,

07:20.153 --> 07:24.180
the very data assets that we
create and that we curate,

07:24.180 --> 07:27.090
they come from the trading organization.

07:27.090 --> 07:29.190
They are very separate from research.

07:29.190 --> 07:32.550
Those data assets include
hedge fund positioning

07:32.550 --> 07:35.400
from our Prime business,
where we sit, for example.

07:35.400 --> 07:39.300
They include all of our
analysis around social media,

07:39.300 --> 07:42.690
social media sentiment, as a
lens on the retail investor,

07:42.690 --> 07:44.850
which has become so significant.

07:44.850 --> 07:47.970
Those data assets, they sit
within the trading organization,

07:47.970 --> 07:51.390
and therefore, we sit within
the trading organization.

07:51.390 --> 07:55.500
Second of all, this very
tactical intraday activity,

07:55.500 --> 07:57.750
these insights, that very often sits

07:57.750 --> 08:00.720
within the trading organization
across the industry,

08:00.720 --> 08:03.180
and indeed it sits within the
trading organization here.

08:03.180 --> 08:05.190
Yeah, that's very clear. Thank you.

08:05.190 --> 08:06.650
And actually, I'd like
to pick up on that point

08:06.650 --> 08:08.100
of the datasets.

08:08.100 --> 08:09.600
You know, I know, as a team,

08:09.600 --> 08:12.420
we are responsible for creating datasets,

08:12.420 --> 08:15.150
these predictive trading
datasets and insights.

08:15.150 --> 08:17.820
But could you expand a bit
about what that actually means

08:17.820 --> 08:19.830
and looks like in practice?

08:19.830 --> 08:20.663
Definitely.

08:20.663 --> 08:23.550
And before going into
detail on perhaps one

08:23.550 --> 08:24.870
or two of those datasets,

08:24.870 --> 08:27.450
it's worth noting that in
creating these datasets

08:27.450 --> 08:29.580
and in providing insights
on those datasets,

08:29.580 --> 08:32.220
we are striving to really open the box,

08:32.220 --> 08:34.650
open the lid on our analysis,

08:34.650 --> 08:38.880
so that we are not simply
presenting opinions and views,

08:38.880 --> 08:42.120
but we are actually fully
open source in a sense.

08:42.120 --> 08:45.810
If we have a view on a market
or a stock or an asset,

08:45.810 --> 08:47.370
yes, you can listen to the opinion,

08:47.370 --> 08:48.900
you can listen to our podcast,

08:48.900 --> 08:51.270
you can read our written
content on that opinion,

08:51.270 --> 08:55.020
but you can also download the
dataset behind that opinion

08:55.020 --> 08:57.630
via an API, do the analysis yourself,

08:57.630 --> 08:59.670
stress test that analysis yourself,

08:59.670 --> 09:03.390
and importantly, critically
utilize that in the future.

09:03.390 --> 09:06.750
So you don't have to speak to
us every minute of every day,

09:06.750 --> 09:08.850
but you can put that dataset in

09:08.850 --> 09:10.650
with all of the other datasets you source

09:10.650 --> 09:13.830
in order to see how that view
will materialize through time.

09:13.830 --> 09:15.510
And I think that's so critical,

09:15.510 --> 09:18.120
that's why we are creating
data-driven insights.

09:18.120 --> 09:21.060
And we are both making the
insights themselves available,

09:21.060 --> 09:23.010
but also the underlying datasets.

09:23.010 --> 09:26.250
It's all about opening
up, being transparent,

09:26.250 --> 09:28.320
being as unbiased as possible.

09:28.320 --> 09:30.900
We're showing our workings,
which, I think, is so critical.

09:30.900 --> 09:32.520
My obvious next question is,

09:32.520 --> 09:34.920
what do those datasets actually look like?

09:34.920 --> 09:38.070
And in terms of the
creation of new datasets,

09:38.070 --> 09:40.320
how do you go about that process?

09:40.320 --> 09:42.840
Yes, well, it's a great question,

09:42.840 --> 09:46.230
and it's worth bearing in mind
that our datasets should be,

09:46.230 --> 09:50.550
we strive for them to be,
as proprietary as possible.

09:50.550 --> 09:51.383
And by that,

09:51.383 --> 09:53.970
I mean we are either leveraging
proprietary data assets

09:53.970 --> 09:56.043
that sit within our organization,

09:57.060 --> 10:00.300
and/or we're leveraging
proprietary techniques

10:00.300 --> 10:03.720
on top of perhaps publicly
available data sources

10:03.720 --> 10:06.120
or commercially available data sources.

10:06.120 --> 10:09.690
But we are using the full breadth, scale,

10:09.690 --> 10:11.310
and technological capabilities

10:11.310 --> 10:13.890
that we have available
to us at J.P. Morgan

10:13.890 --> 10:17.490
to create proprietary
analytics on those datasets.

10:17.490 --> 10:20.670
So let me give one
example, Prime positioning.

10:20.670 --> 10:23.970
By that, I mean we look at the aggregated

10:23.970 --> 10:27.720
and the critically anonymized collation

10:27.720 --> 10:31.200
of hedge fund positions
from our Prime book.

10:31.200 --> 10:36.150
This is a give-to-get model,
clients opt in to this dataset,

10:36.150 --> 10:38.370
but to the extent that the vast majority

10:38.370 --> 10:40.740
of our clients do opt in to that dataset,

10:40.740 --> 10:44.430
we create an aggregated
and an anonymized lens

10:44.430 --> 10:47.550
on the positioning of those
clients in given stocks

10:47.550 --> 10:51.420
and in given indices and markets
at a given point in time,

10:51.420 --> 10:55.140
on a daily basis, lagged
by three days in this case.

10:55.140 --> 10:57.840
Now, it's absolutely critical

10:57.840 --> 11:01.560
that this dataset is
aggregated and anonymized,

11:01.560 --> 11:04.110
so that our clients feel comfortable

11:04.110 --> 11:08.070
that no individual client
position can be back-derived.

11:08.070 --> 11:09.240
And that's really critical.

11:09.240 --> 11:10.530
It's absolutely critical.

11:10.530 --> 11:12.960
So what sort of techniques
do we use to ensure

11:12.960 --> 11:14.280
that that is the case?

11:14.280 --> 11:17.430
We use, for example, winsorization.

11:17.430 --> 11:20.730
By that, I mean we chop off
the tails of a distribution,

11:20.730 --> 11:25.237
so that any extreme position
is normalized and is taken out.

11:25.237 --> 11:26.550
We bucketize.

11:26.550 --> 11:29.430
And by that, I mean we don't
provide precise numbers

11:29.430 --> 11:31.650
for all of our datasets, but
for some of our datasets,

11:31.650 --> 11:34.350
we just simply put them
into buckets, like deciles.

11:34.350 --> 11:36.420
And therefore, you can
only see if it changes

11:36.420 --> 11:39.270
if it moves from one bucket to another.

11:39.270 --> 11:40.620
We cap weightings,

11:40.620 --> 11:44.190
so if a given client or a
given client's position exceeds

11:44.190 --> 11:46.920
a given percent waiting, we will cap it

11:46.920 --> 11:49.980
to ensure that outsized
positions aren't showcased.

11:49.980 --> 11:53.640
These enhancements are absolutely
critical to the dataset,

11:53.640 --> 11:55.380
most importantly to make sure

11:55.380 --> 11:57.630
that they are truly anonymized,

11:57.630 --> 12:00.150
but also to make sure that
we're taking out extremes,

12:00.150 --> 12:03.270
so that we have a
representative series over time

12:03.270 --> 12:04.800
for our dataset.

12:04.800 --> 12:07.470
So that's our Prime
positioning hedge fund dataset,

12:07.470 --> 12:08.880
for example.

12:08.880 --> 12:12.150
That's very clearly
leveraging proprietary data

12:12.150 --> 12:14.970
that we have available to
us as a result of the scale

12:14.970 --> 12:16.890
of the Prime business here.

12:16.890 --> 12:20.820
Now, to give another example,
which is not, at its genesis,

12:20.820 --> 12:25.140
utilizing a proprietary dataset,
but does, I would argue,

12:25.140 --> 12:28.110
utilize a proprietary
analytical technique,

12:28.110 --> 12:30.180
this would be our social media,

12:30.180 --> 12:33.000
social sentiment dataset,
which you know so well.

12:33.000 --> 12:35.640
Here, again, it's a single-stock dataset,

12:35.640 --> 12:39.120
it has significant history,
going back to 2009.

12:39.120 --> 12:41.400
It's provided on a daily basis.

12:41.400 --> 12:44.160
Here, we are ultimately
developing relationships

12:44.160 --> 12:46.350
with social media companies.

12:46.350 --> 12:50.550
We have a paid-for license
with them to utilize it,

12:50.550 --> 12:54.480
to aggregate it, but this
is an enormous dataset,

12:54.480 --> 12:58.050
and it's very hard to disentangle
a signal from that noise,

12:58.050 --> 12:58.920
so to speak.

12:58.920 --> 13:01.560
And social media is a fantastic lens

13:01.560 --> 13:03.300
by which you can understand

13:03.300 --> 13:05.940
or try and understand
retail investor activity.

13:05.940 --> 13:08.340
And it has been quite
a feat to ingest that

13:08.340 --> 13:11.370
in such a way that we believe
it has predictive power,

13:11.370 --> 13:14.430
we believe it has use for
the investment process

13:14.430 --> 13:18.120
for us internally within
J.P.Morgan and for our client base.

13:18.120 --> 13:20.760
So what have we done here
in terms of the process?

13:20.760 --> 13:23.850
Well, even to ingest
these millions of posts

13:23.850 --> 13:27.510
that are available to us,
we have to spike-detect,

13:27.510 --> 13:30.510
we can't possibly bring
them all in to our platform.

13:30.510 --> 13:32.700
That alone is just too much data.

13:32.700 --> 13:36.000
So we have to spike-detect to identify

13:36.000 --> 13:38.910
which data points we believe
are worthy of coming in.

13:38.910 --> 13:40.590
They are either data points that relate

13:40.590 --> 13:42.750
to specific assets that we care about,

13:42.750 --> 13:45.960
for example, we track
3,000 stocks within the US,

13:45.960 --> 13:47.160
and/or they're posts

13:47.160 --> 13:49.500
that have significantly
increased over time,

13:49.500 --> 13:51.780
which warrants their inclusion.

13:51.780 --> 13:53.400
So first of all, we do that.

13:53.400 --> 13:55.800
We then need to entity-map those posts

13:55.800 --> 13:58.620
to determine which stocks or assets

13:58.620 --> 14:00.210
or entities they relate to.

14:00.210 --> 14:04.560
For example, if we are looking
at posts relating to apple,

14:04.560 --> 14:06.240
are we taking apple, the fruit,

14:06.240 --> 14:08.730
or are we taking Apple, the company?

14:08.730 --> 14:10.890
That in itself is such
a critical distinction.

14:10.890 --> 14:12.480
So we've had to use our partners

14:12.480 --> 14:14.340
in the Machine Learning
Center of Excellence,

14:14.340 --> 14:18.810
their techniques, to correctly,
or as accurately as we can,

14:18.810 --> 14:21.060
entity-map all of these posts

14:21.060 --> 14:24.630
to real financial assets
that we care about.

14:24.630 --> 14:27.030
We not only create a volumes dataset,

14:27.030 --> 14:28.740
which is really how many posts are there

14:28.740 --> 14:32.100
for a given asset on
a given day over time,

14:32.100 --> 14:33.840
but we also need to create the sentiment

14:33.840 --> 14:36.690
related to those posts over time.

14:36.690 --> 14:38.910
And sentiment analysis,

14:38.910 --> 14:40.650
I mean, it's really
evolved over the years.

14:40.650 --> 14:43.350
10 years ago, we utilized traditional NLP,

14:43.350 --> 14:46.290
natural language processing,
and very traditional,

14:46.290 --> 14:48.960
arguably quite simplistic approaches were,

14:48.960 --> 14:50.550
for example, bag of words.

14:50.550 --> 14:54.210
Let's get bag of positive
words, like upbeat,

14:54.210 --> 14:57.420
and a bag of negative words,
like down, disappoint,

14:57.420 --> 15:00.480
and let's map those posts
to that bag of words

15:00.480 --> 15:04.020
to infer a sentiment
for those interactions.

15:04.020 --> 15:06.960
But thankfully, technology
has enormously helped us

15:06.960 --> 15:07.923
with that job.

15:09.090 --> 15:13.012
We can now leverage LLMs to
help annotate different posts,

15:13.012 --> 15:16.290
which has been transformational,
as you mentioned earlier.

15:16.290 --> 15:20.160
We also leverage transformer
models on the NLPs,

15:20.160 --> 15:24.990
for example, Google's BERT
model and Facebook's RoBERTa,

15:24.990 --> 15:27.930
really, an augmentation
of Google's BERT model,

15:27.930 --> 15:30.120
we utilize that specifically

15:30.120 --> 15:32.160
to aid this sentiment generation process.

15:32.160 --> 15:34.020
And to be able to look at that nuance

15:34.020 --> 15:36.690
that's not simply positive or negative,

15:36.690 --> 15:39.240
and actually incredibly topical
to be talking about this,

15:39.240 --> 15:41.700
because we've seen a big resurgence

15:41.700 --> 15:43.290
of the retail investor this year,

15:43.290 --> 15:45.720
and in fact, the meme phenomena come back.

15:45.720 --> 15:49.440
So this is a very topical
dataset that's highly,

15:49.440 --> 15:51.540
or highly utilized by our clients.

15:51.540 --> 15:52.590
Yeah, absolutely.

15:52.590 --> 15:53.913
And when I think about the datasets

15:53.913 --> 15:56.400
that our clients are
asking us the most for,

15:56.400 --> 16:00.600
I would say it comes down
to positioning, flows,

16:00.600 --> 16:03.600
sentiment based on as
many sources as possible,

16:03.600 --> 16:05.790
and textual data, as you mentioned before.

16:05.790 --> 16:07.470
I think all of those topics come up.

16:07.470 --> 16:08.520
I agree.

16:08.520 --> 16:10.590
And so what have we been
developing in that space?

16:10.590 --> 16:12.000
Well, on the positioning side,

16:12.000 --> 16:14.700
we obviously have our hedge
fund positioning dataset.

16:14.700 --> 16:16.290
We augment that with positioning

16:16.290 --> 16:18.960
from as many other investor
types as we can track.

16:18.960 --> 16:21.360
So we look at retail investor flows,

16:21.360 --> 16:23.340
which, as you say, have been on the rise,

16:23.340 --> 16:26.790
particularly post-COVID,
and indeed this year.

16:26.790 --> 16:28.830
We look at ETF flows,

16:28.830 --> 16:32.490
we look at CTA, inferred CTA positioning,

16:32.490 --> 16:34.680
we look at mutual fund positioning.

16:34.680 --> 16:37.080
We aggregate all of that
together to have a lens

16:37.080 --> 16:39.150
on the aggregation of that positioning,

16:39.150 --> 16:40.950
that's our tactical positioning monitor,

16:40.950 --> 16:42.930
which itself is another dataset.

16:42.930 --> 16:45.000
That's the positioning and flows lens.

16:45.000 --> 16:47.970
We then have an equivalent for sentiment.

16:47.970 --> 16:49.710
We obviously have social sentiment,

16:49.710 --> 16:51.390
a lens on the retail investor.

16:51.390 --> 16:53.280
We now have professional sentiment,

16:53.280 --> 16:55.770
a lens on the institutional investor.

16:55.770 --> 16:58.500
And we have the aggregated
tactical sentiment monitor,

16:58.500 --> 17:00.600
which really pulls all of these together.

17:00.600 --> 17:03.420
And of course, we could talk
about the predictive power

17:03.420 --> 17:04.980
of each one of these series,

17:04.980 --> 17:08.130
which is a whole another debate.

17:08.130 --> 17:09.570
But that is absolutely critical

17:09.570 --> 17:11.520
when we're having our
conversations with our clients,

17:11.520 --> 17:13.380
it's not only, "What data do you have?

17:13.380 --> 17:16.230
What are the attributes of those
datasets? How much history?

17:16.230 --> 17:19.080
How much lag? How can I access it?"

17:19.080 --> 17:21.870
But it's also, "What are
the lessons you've learned?

17:21.870 --> 17:24.930
What are the predictive analytics
that you've learned so far

17:24.930 --> 17:26.460
through all of your back tests?"

17:26.460 --> 17:30.240
So there are obviously so many
datasets that we can look at,

17:30.240 --> 17:31.410
that we can create.

17:31.410 --> 17:32.820
There's such a journey in front of us

17:32.820 --> 17:34.770
in terms of continuing to enhance this.

17:34.770 --> 17:36.810
And of course, we are always client-led.

17:36.810 --> 17:38.730
And Edwina, you are
speaking to the clients,

17:38.730 --> 17:42.330
you are hearing from them
about what they want to see.

17:42.330 --> 17:45.450
Can you speak to what
clients have been asking for,

17:45.450 --> 17:48.810
and also how we determine
which datasets to prioritize?

17:48.810 --> 17:50.040
Yeah, it's a great question,

17:50.040 --> 17:52.953
and it's a little bit of a
balancing act in reality.

17:54.030 --> 17:56.280
You know, to echo your point,

17:56.280 --> 17:58.020
the client feedback is absolutely critical

17:58.020 --> 18:00.180
in terms of determining our pipeline

18:00.180 --> 18:01.950
and where we allocate resource.

18:01.950 --> 18:04.470
You know, just to be
very clear about this,

18:04.470 --> 18:08.460
bringing a new dataset to market
is a considerable endeavor

18:08.460 --> 18:10.080
and doesn't just involve our team.

18:10.080 --> 18:12.780
We work with, as the
point you made earlier,

18:12.780 --> 18:15.780
our partners across the
business at J.P. Morgan.

18:15.780 --> 18:17.100
So we really need to make sure

18:17.100 --> 18:19.920
that when we put that effort
in and allocate that resource,

18:19.920 --> 18:22.770
that we have the client
demand to make it worthwhile.

18:22.770 --> 18:24.540
But that also has to be balanced

18:24.540 --> 18:26.310
with what's actually realistic,

18:26.310 --> 18:29.250
you know, in terms of really
boring things perhaps,

18:29.250 --> 18:31.860
but things like licensing
are absolutely critical.

18:31.860 --> 18:33.780
And when you talk about proprietary data,

18:33.780 --> 18:37.500
that comes with a whole host
of sensitivities around it.

18:37.500 --> 18:40.170
But in terms of what's
actually being demanded,

18:40.170 --> 18:44.070
or, sorry, in terms of
where the client demand is,

18:44.070 --> 18:48.330
I would say that the rise
of sentiment as a theme,

18:48.330 --> 18:50.400
so wanting to understand,

18:50.400 --> 18:52.650
through a variety of different sources,

18:52.650 --> 18:55.170
what different investor
types are thinking about,

18:55.170 --> 18:58.890
or where the sentiment sits, is key.

18:58.890 --> 19:01.710
So you talked about social media

19:01.710 --> 19:03.450
as a lens for the retail investor,

19:03.450 --> 19:06.510
but what we're now trying to
do is broaden those horizons

19:06.510 --> 19:08.610
to try and have a lens on sentiment

19:08.610 --> 19:10.800
for the institutional investor.

19:10.800 --> 19:11.633
And of course,

19:11.633 --> 19:13.140
when we talk about the
institutional investor,

19:13.140 --> 19:15.600
there are a variety of
different investor types

19:15.600 --> 19:17.490
within that bucket.

19:17.490 --> 19:22.490
But an area that we're expanding
upon is looking at reports

19:23.940 --> 19:27.030
or documentation from the industry

19:27.030 --> 19:30.420
to try and understand
institutional sentiment.

19:30.420 --> 19:32.160
And then, obviously, within that,

19:32.160 --> 19:33.420
there's more that we can do.

19:33.420 --> 19:36.420
So we could look at
different types of client,

19:36.420 --> 19:38.490
or different types of investor,

19:38.490 --> 19:41.520
and we could also look at, for
example, regional variations.

19:41.520 --> 19:43.020
There's a lot we can do there.

19:43.020 --> 19:43.853
Absolutely.

19:43.853 --> 19:46.110
And that demand for institutional,

19:46.110 --> 19:50.250
professional textual content
is so rife right now, isn't it?

19:50.250 --> 19:53.340
And that demand to consume it
in a machine-readable form,

19:53.340 --> 19:56.551
so that it can be put
into the knowledge bases

19:56.551 --> 19:58.440
of our investing clients.

19:58.440 --> 20:00.660
And whenever we present these datasets,

20:00.660 --> 20:03.660
it's so important for us to
put them in a market's context

20:03.660 --> 20:07.110
and to look at them continuously
through a market's context.

20:07.110 --> 20:09.060
Just to give a couple of examples,

20:09.060 --> 20:13.020
when we went through the real
market lows in early April,

20:13.020 --> 20:17.310
the S&P 500, it dropped around
20% post Liberation Day.

20:17.310 --> 20:20.250
And at that time, our
positioning datasets,

20:20.250 --> 20:22.530
and specifically our
tactical positioning monitor,

20:22.530 --> 20:25.530
it fell dramatically,
and it actually triggered

20:25.530 --> 20:28.050
an attractive signal
based on our back tests.

20:28.050 --> 20:30.270
And this is something that our
Positioning Intelligence team

20:30.270 --> 20:31.710
regularly write about.

20:31.710 --> 20:34.500
But even more powerful
was to have an awareness

20:34.500 --> 20:36.120
of the market dynamics at the time,

20:36.120 --> 20:37.920
the fact that developments

20:37.920 --> 20:41.370
in the US political
situation were very rapid.

20:41.370 --> 20:44.430
We had the 90-day pause
in tariffs announced.

20:44.430 --> 20:46.140
And perhaps, as a result of that,

20:46.140 --> 20:49.320
coupled with fact that
positioning levels were low,

20:49.320 --> 20:52.200
which is historically quite
a ripe time to buy equities,

20:52.200 --> 20:53.340
markets then rebounded.

20:53.340 --> 20:55.740
And we've continued to see
markets rebound since then,

20:55.740 --> 20:57.480
driven by the retail investor,

20:57.480 --> 20:59.670
which comes back to all
of our retail datasets,

20:59.670 --> 21:02.580
retail flows, retail net flows increasing,

21:02.580 --> 21:04.770
retail sentiment never
actually got as light,

21:04.770 --> 21:06.120
and it has been increasing.

21:06.120 --> 21:09.960
So I think putting these datasets
into the market's context,

21:09.960 --> 21:13.620
so that when we're using them
real time on an ongoing basis,

21:13.620 --> 21:17.250
we can either read the
datasets as they are,

21:17.250 --> 21:19.020
through a purely systematic basis,

21:19.020 --> 21:20.640
which has an enormous amount of merit,

21:20.640 --> 21:23.790
is arguably the most unbiased
way of looking at the data,

21:23.790 --> 21:26.010
or we can add that quantitative view

21:26.010 --> 21:27.510
to more of a discretionary view

21:27.510 --> 21:30.510
in terms of how catalysts in
the market are playing out

21:30.510 --> 21:35.310
to come up with more of a
quantamental or a combined view,

21:35.310 --> 21:38.370
marrying the systematic
with the discretionary view.

21:38.370 --> 21:39.401
That's also so powerful.

21:39.401 --> 21:42.810
And really, as a team,
we strive to do both.

21:42.810 --> 21:45.060
Well, arguably, that's
where our edge lies.

21:45.060 --> 21:45.893
Yes, indeed.

21:45.893 --> 21:47.250
So it's pulling together those threads

21:47.250 --> 21:48.420
from our market intelligence,

21:48.420 --> 21:51.900
who are tracking markets
real time through the day,

21:51.900 --> 21:53.490
leveraging these datasets,

21:53.490 --> 21:55.050
with our Positioning Intelligence team,

21:55.050 --> 21:56.430
who are doing exactly that,

21:56.430 --> 21:59.490
but specifically focused
on positioning data,

21:59.490 --> 22:01.140
to our Data Intelligence team,

22:01.140 --> 22:03.930
which is much more the
data science capabilities,

22:03.930 --> 22:06.540
creating these datasets,
such as social media,

22:06.540 --> 22:09.390
It's combining, it's that
aggregation of them all

22:09.390 --> 22:11.280
that we believe to be so powerful.

22:11.280 --> 22:12.360
And really, that's at the heart

22:12.360 --> 22:14.280
of what our clients are
looking for from us,

22:14.280 --> 22:16.650
is bringing those threads together

22:16.650 --> 22:19.110
to provide that combined lens.

22:19.110 --> 22:19.943
Absolutely.

22:19.943 --> 22:22.470
And isn't it so interesting
and such a privilege for us

22:22.470 --> 22:25.200
to be facing all of these
different investor types,

22:25.200 --> 22:27.810
from the quants to the discretionary,

22:27.810 --> 22:29.370
to everything in between,

22:29.370 --> 22:33.463
from the portfolio managers and
the analysts to the traders,

22:33.463 --> 22:36.000
to the central data-sourcing teams,

22:36.000 --> 22:38.280
and to hear about their
evolving client needs,

22:38.280 --> 22:40.170
which are evolving so rapidly,

22:40.170 --> 22:43.110
and to be doing our best
to service those needs?

22:43.110 --> 22:45.090
Eloise, I've heard you speak compellingly

22:45.090 --> 22:47.730
in the past about continuous learning,

22:47.730 --> 22:51.480
and, you know, really honing
intellectual curiosity.

22:51.480 --> 22:53.880
Could you talk a little bit
about what that means to you

22:53.880 --> 22:55.530
and what you do in practice?

22:55.530 --> 22:58.200
I mean, I do think it entails
listening to the client,

22:58.200 --> 23:00.810
the voice of the client,
that's absolutely critical.

23:00.810 --> 23:05.010
It also entails being
willing to accept feedback.

23:05.010 --> 23:07.260
It's not always fun learning that you need

23:07.260 --> 23:10.200
to change something, you need
to create something different.

23:10.200 --> 23:11.340
You don't know where to start

23:11.340 --> 23:13.980
in terms of identifying a new data point.

23:13.980 --> 23:15.600
But at the end of the day,

23:15.600 --> 23:19.500
it's only hearing all of those
requests that gives us a lens

23:19.500 --> 23:22.320
on our clients and how they're evolving,

23:22.320 --> 23:23.520
and what they want.

23:23.520 --> 23:25.260
And it's the cumulation of all of that,

23:25.260 --> 23:28.710
it's the iterative process
of all of those discussions,

23:28.710 --> 23:32.130
that really builds our
knowledge base over time,

23:32.130 --> 23:34.980
and that really builds our capability

23:34.980 --> 23:36.330
to service our clients over time.

23:36.330 --> 23:38.460
And I really embrace that. I love that.

23:38.460 --> 23:39.840
What do you think, Edwina?

23:39.840 --> 23:41.070
I think it's a great point,

23:41.070 --> 23:43.470
but in terms of what
it actually looks like,

23:43.470 --> 23:45.570
I mean, I'll speak for myself personally,

23:45.570 --> 23:49.350
I make an effort every morning
to start with listening

23:49.350 --> 23:52.380
to a 10-minute news briefing,
so that I have some idea

23:52.380 --> 23:54.540
of what's going on in the
market and the wider world.

23:54.540 --> 23:57.750
I find that 10 minutes are
very manageable amount of time.

23:57.750 --> 24:01.560
And actually, the cumulative
effect of that is significant.

24:01.560 --> 24:03.990
I also like scanning the newspapers

24:03.990 --> 24:05.340
and understanding what's going on.

24:05.340 --> 24:08.340
And then, you know, without
doubt, our colleagues,

24:08.340 --> 24:11.220
whether that's within our own
team, and we all sit together,

24:11.220 --> 24:13.200
or across the wider business,

24:13.200 --> 24:15.420
but maintaining that curiosity,

24:15.420 --> 24:20.070
and that seeing learning as
an ongoing thing, is vital.

24:20.070 --> 24:22.740
It's vital for continuous development

24:22.740 --> 24:25.320
and for being the best we can possibly be.

24:25.320 --> 24:27.810
And I'd like to talk to you a
little bit about mentorship,

24:27.810 --> 24:30.150
both in terms of mentors for you,

24:30.150 --> 24:34.230
or being a mentor to people who
are earlier in their career.

24:34.230 --> 24:36.000
What does that mean to you?

24:36.000 --> 24:40.020
It's so important to continuously mentor,

24:40.020 --> 24:43.290
whether that's a formal
mentee-mentor relationship,

24:43.290 --> 24:46.500
or more commonly, I would
argue, across the industry,

24:46.500 --> 24:49.050
and for me, it's more
of an informal thing.

24:49.050 --> 24:50.490
It's so important.

24:50.490 --> 24:53.250
I mean, if I look at my mentors,

24:53.250 --> 24:57.330
I almost call them our team
stakeholders, as you know.

24:57.330 --> 25:00.510
And for a team like ours
that's somewhat hybrid,

25:00.510 --> 25:03.870
that sits within trading,
that's very close to research,

25:03.870 --> 25:05.190
that's very close to sales,

25:05.190 --> 25:07.710
that's very close to the data science

25:07.710 --> 25:09.930
and the data-driven parts
of our organization,

25:09.930 --> 25:11.850
we have many stakeholders.

25:11.850 --> 25:14.520
And yes, that's a responsibility,

25:14.520 --> 25:16.440
because we need to make
sure that what we are doing

25:16.440 --> 25:18.600
is fully aligned with their businesses,

25:18.600 --> 25:22.380
but is also such a privilege,
such an opportunity,

25:22.380 --> 25:25.740
to have those relationships
with those individuals.

25:25.740 --> 25:27.570
All of those relationships different.

25:27.570 --> 25:30.390
But I really try to
take on board the advice

25:30.390 --> 25:32.790
that they will give me, and give our team,

25:32.790 --> 25:34.470
in helping to steer our team

25:34.470 --> 25:37.560
in the most effective
commercial direction.

25:37.560 --> 25:40.620
I see those, in a sense,
as mentoring relationships,

25:40.620 --> 25:42.870
because those people are, in good faith,

25:42.870 --> 25:45.870
giving the best advice they
can to me and to our team.

25:45.870 --> 25:48.330
And I really value those relationships.

25:48.330 --> 25:51.810
But equally, the importance
of mentoring others,

25:51.810 --> 25:55.050
guiding others, supporting
others, it can't be understated.

25:55.050 --> 25:58.170
I think for individuals in
the organization to know

25:58.170 --> 25:59.520
that we are all approachable,

25:59.520 --> 26:00.870
we should all be approachable,

26:00.870 --> 26:04.500
and that we all will take
the time to hear concerns,

26:04.500 --> 26:08.010
to hear challenges, and to
provide our feedback on that,

26:08.010 --> 26:09.540
I think it's completely critical

26:09.540 --> 26:11.490
for the ecosystem to work well.

26:11.490 --> 26:13.290
It's also, by the way,

26:13.290 --> 26:16.080
as powerful for the mentor as the mentee.

26:16.080 --> 26:19.200
And I truly believe that, in all senses.

26:19.200 --> 26:20.100
You know, for myself,

26:20.100 --> 26:22.140
if I meet with someone
in a different business,

26:22.140 --> 26:24.300
or perhaps in a business
that's closer to us,

26:24.300 --> 26:26.520
and I hear their challenges
and their concerns,

26:26.520 --> 26:28.890
I always learn something new.

26:28.890 --> 26:30.810
I love being able to help to the extent

26:30.810 --> 26:33.813
that I think I've got experience
that might be relevant.

26:35.160 --> 26:38.088
And I so often am reminded
of things which are critical

26:38.088 --> 26:40.260
to my own career and to our own team

26:40.260 --> 26:41.430
and to our own development.

26:41.430 --> 26:44.910
So I do see these relationships,

26:44.910 --> 26:46.440
they don't need to be formalized.

26:46.440 --> 26:51.030
In fact, overly formalizing
them can take away

26:51.030 --> 26:52.680
from the natural rapport

26:52.680 --> 26:55.363
and the natural dialogue and
conversation that's required.

26:55.363 --> 26:57.510
But I do believe they're really important.

26:57.510 --> 27:00.690
Another attribute that I
think is really important,

27:00.690 --> 27:02.040
and perhaps underestimating,

27:02.040 --> 27:06.000
is consistency of
delivery and following up.

27:06.000 --> 27:08.730
And it's relevant when it comes
to stakeholder management,

27:08.730 --> 27:10.380
mentee-mentorship.

27:10.380 --> 27:15.380
I always love it when people
that I've mentored follow up

27:15.600 --> 27:18.450
with interesting snippets,
interesting articles,

27:18.450 --> 27:20.790
podcast recommendations, pieces of news.

27:20.790 --> 27:22.020
I love it when they do that,

27:22.020 --> 27:24.210
because it's strengthening
our relationship,

27:24.210 --> 27:27.000
it's keeping that line
of communication open,

27:27.000 --> 27:29.490
which means the probability of
us reaching out to each other

27:29.490 --> 27:32.040
in the future is that much higher.

27:32.040 --> 27:33.720
It's also truly informative,

27:33.720 --> 27:37.620
and we learn much more from
each other through that process.

27:37.620 --> 27:40.440
And I think that's so
important in all directions.

27:40.440 --> 27:42.630
So the significance of following up,

27:42.630 --> 27:45.780
of consistently doing
what you said you'd do,

27:45.780 --> 27:48.330
of consistently following through,

27:48.330 --> 27:51.210
it does ultimately require
a lot of hard work.

27:51.210 --> 27:53.880
And perhaps that sounds boring,
perhaps that sounds dry,

27:53.880 --> 27:58.350
but to me, that is the greatest
inspiration for creativity.

